Market Risk

Iaki Gangutia

The purpose of this project is to show how a Stochastic Geometric Brownian Movement Process can be applied to the finance sector, specifically to model Market Risk. As an example we will use the data related to the Standard & Poors 500 (S&P 500), the most common, famous and reference index to follow the United States Economy.

We will use this type of process to model the evolution of a random system through time with a non constant random variable, being the growth of this variable exponential and with a non constant volatility as the moment value increases.

To start we will load some packages needed for our project, each one with a purpose.

We proceed to convert the prices to logarithms and calculate the returns.

log_returns = np.diff(np.log(sp500_prices))

Now we will get some needed historical parameters for the Euler method.

In[6]:
S0 = sp500_prices.iloc[-1]  # Initial price
mu = np.mean(log_returns)  # Expected return (drift)
sigma = np.std(log_returns)  # Expected volatility

As it follows, we will set the rest of parameters for the Euler method.

In[7]:
dt = 0.05  # Time step unit
T = 252  # Horizon Time (one trading year)
n_sim = int(T / dt)  # n simulations
n_tra = 1000  # n trajectories

Euler method for Geometric Brownian Motion

This function will allow us to calculate various simulations and trajectories in base of the previous parameters. It is important to mention, that this method is an approximate numerical solution of the Stochastic Differential Equation (SDE).

In[8]:
def GBM(S0, mu, sigma, dt, n_sim, n_tra):
    
    trajectories = []  # Trajectories storage
    
    # Iterate to generate trajectories
    for tra in range(n_tra):
        
        trajectory = np.full(n_sim + 1, np.nan)  # Current trajetory storage

        trajectory[0] = S0  # Set initial price
        
        
        # Iterate to calculate price changes
        for t in range(n_sim):
            
            # Euler Method
            Z = np.random.normal(0, 1)  # Standard normal random variable

            delta_S = mu * trajectory[t] * dt + sigma * trajectory[t] * np.sqrt(dt) * Z  # Delta S
            
            trajectory[t + 1] = trajectory[t] + delta_S  # Next price
            
            
        trajectories.append(trajectory)  # Add current trajectory
        
        
    return trajectories

Function call.

In[9]:
simulations_trajectories = GBM(S0, mu, sigma, dt, n_sim, n_tra)

The Value at Risk (VaR) is a measure that will quantify the maximum risk of loss of our active over a given period of time and with a specific confidence level.

In[13]:
def VaR_func(alpha):
    
    last_values = array_trajectories[:, -1]
    var_value = np.quantile(last_values, alpha)
    VaR = round(S0 - var_value, 2)
    
    return VaR

The Conditional Value at Risk (CVaR) is a measure that provides an estimate of the expected value of losses in the worst case scenario, being the weighted average of losses exceeding VaR for the confidence level given.

In[14]:
def CVaR_func(alpha):
    
    last_values = array_trajectories[:, -1]
    cvar_vec = last_values[last_values < np.quantile(last_values, alpha)]
    CVaR = round(S0 - np.mean(cvar_vec), 2)
    
    return CVaR

The Maximum Drawdown is the peak-to-trough decline in our active over a given period of time.

In[15]:
def max_drawdown_func():
    
    max_drawdowns = []
    
    for trajectory in simulations_trajectories:
        
        peak = np.maximum.accumulate(trajectory)
        drawdowns = peak - trajectory
        max_drawdowns.append(max(drawdowns))
        
    max_aggregated = round(max(max_drawdowns), 2)

    return max_aggregated

Finally, we call the previous defined functions using an alpha of 0.01 or 1% and we create a data frame to show them together.

In[16]:
alpha = 0.01 # 99% confidence interval

VaR = VaR_func(alpha)
CVaR = CVaR_func(alpha)

Risk_Measurement = pd.DataFrame({"VaR": VaR,
                                 "CVaR": CVaR,
                                 "Maximum_Drawdown": max_drawdown_func()}, 
                                index = ["S&P 500"])
